{{Infobox University |name = School of Journalism Carlos Septién García |native_name = Escuela de Periodismo Carlos Septién García |image_name = |image_size = |caption = |latin_name = |motto = |mottoeng = |established = May 30, 1949 |closed = |type = |affiliation = |endowment = |officer_in_charge = |chairman = |chancellor = |president = |vice-president = |superintendent = |provost = |vice_chancellor = |rector = |principal = |dean = |director = José Luis Vázquez Baeza |head_label = |head = |faculty = |staff = |students = |undergrad = |postgrad = |doctoral = |other = |city = Delegation Cuauhtémoc, [[Mexico City]] |state = [[Distrito Federal de México|Mexico, D.F.]] |province = |country = [[Mexico]] |coor = |campus = |former_names = |free_label = |free = |sports = |colors = |colours = |nickname = |mascot = |athletics = |affiliations = |website = [http://www.septien.edu.mx/epcsg www.septien.edu.mx/epcsg] |logo = |footnotes = }}
The '''Escuela de Periodismo Carlos Septién García''' (EPCSG - ''School of Journalism Carlos Septién García'') was the first [[Mexico|Mexican]] educational institution of [[journalism]]. It was founded by [[Luis Beltrán y Mendoza]], and supported by the [[Acción Católica Mexicana]] (Mexican [[Catholic Action]]), on May 30, 1939, and achieved certification of the [[Secretaría de Educación Pública]] on July 2, 1976. The school was named after its second director.
Under the leadership of Alejandro Avilés Insunza the school detached itself from the Acción Católica Mexicana and its associated political and ideological tendencies concerning [[academic freedom]].<ref>[http://www.septien.edu.mx/institucional/presentacion.htm ''Escuela de Periodismo Carlos Septién García''] (Spanish).</ref>
