{{Infobox person | name = Marilee Jones | image = <!-- Only freely-licensed images may be used to depict living people. See [[WP:NONFREE]]. --> | image_size = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1951|06|12}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | education = B.S. 1973, [[The College of Saint Rose]] | occupation = Former dean of admissions, [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] | spouse = Steven R. Bussolari (separated) | parents = | children = Nora }}
'''Marilee Jones''' (born June 12, 1951) is a former [[dean of admissions]] at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT) and the co-author of the popular guide to the college admission process ''Less Stress, More Success: A New Approach to Guiding Your Teen Through College Admissions and Beyond'' (American Academy of Pediatrics, 2006).<ref name="Amazon">[https://www.amazon.com/dp/1581102305 ''Less Stress, More Success'' description from Amazon.com]</ref> The book received critical acclaim and Jones was featured on [[CBS]], [[National Public Radio]], ''[[USA Today]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'',<ref name="MIT">{{cite web|url=http://www.mitadmissions.org/Marilee.shtml |title=Jones' MIT profile |accessdate=2007-04-26 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061027101436/http://www.mitadmissions.org/Marilee.shtml |archivedate=October 27, 2006 |df= }}</ref> and ''[[The Boston Globe]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Marcella|last=Bombardieri|title=What's your pleasure? MIT admissions dean looking for students who enjoy life|url=http://www.boston.com/news/education/higher/articles/2004/03/11/whats_your_pleasure/|publisher=''Boston Globe''|date=March 11, 2004|accessdate=2007-04-26}}</ref> Jones resigned from her position in 2007 when it became known she had fabricated her academic degrees from [[Union College]] and [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]] on a job application in 1979 and she had added a fabricated degree to her resume from [[Albany Medical College]] sometime "after she was hired."<ref name="Hoover">{{cite web | last = Hoover | first = Eric | title = Truth and Admissions: Former MIT Dean Seeks to Reclaim Her Name | publisher = ''[http://chronicle.com The Chronicle of Higher Education]'' | date = 2009-12-06 | url = http://chronicle.com/article/TruthAdmissions-Former/49366/ | accessdate = 2009-12-08 }}</ref> ''The Times'' characterized Jones's earlier prestige as "the guru of the movement to tame the college-admissions frenzy."<ref name="NYT">{{cite news |first=Tamar|last=Lewin|title=Dean of Admissions at M.I.T. Resigns|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/26/education/26cnd-mit.html|publisher=The New York Times|date=April 26, 2007|accessdate=2007-04-26}}</ref> ''The Boston Globe'' called her "the most celebrated and outspoken admissions dean in America."<ref name="globecelebrated"> {{cite web | last = Marcella Bombardieri and | first = Tracy Jan | title = MIT dean quits over fabricated credentials | publisher = ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' | date = 2007-04-27 | url = http://www.boston.com/news/local/articles/2007/04/27/mit_dean_quits_over_fabricated_credentials/ | accessdate = 2007-04-28 }} </ref> After her resignation, she became the number 2 newsmaker of the day on ''COUNTDOWN with Keith Olbermann'' for "begging college applicants not to pad their resumes" while having done so herself.<ref name="globecelebrated"> {{cite web | last = Olbermann | first = Keith | title = COUNTDOWN with Keith Olbermann | publisher = MSNBC | date = 2007-04-27 | url = http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/18400008/ | accessdate = 2009-12-10 }} </ref>
Jones was first hired by MIT as an entry-level admissions officer in 1979; she was later promoted to associate director of admissions. She then served as interim dean of admissions from May 1997 until January 1998, when she was appointed to the position full-time.<ref name="NewDean">{{cite news|url=http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/1997/jones-1217.html |title=Jones is new dean of admissions |publisher=MIT News Office |date=December 17, 1997 |accessdate=2007-04-27}}</ref>
Jones is quoted in [[Daniel Golden]]'s “[[The Price of Admission]]," as describing a [[Korean-American]] student as “yet another textureless math grind.”<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/148996763|title=The price of admission : how America's ruling class buys its way into elite colleges--and who gets left outside the gates|last=1957-|first=Golden, Daniel,|date=2007|publisher=Three Rivers Press|isbn=9781400097975|edition= 1st paperback|location=New York|oclc=148996763}}</ref>
==Resignation== On April 23, 2007, Jones resigned her position after MIT learned she had fabricated her academic degrees from Union College and Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute when she first applied for an entry-level admissions officer position with MIT in 1979<ref name="TheTech"> {{cite news |first=Nick |last=Semenkovich |title=Admissions Dean Resigns After Lying on Résumé |url=http://tech.mit.edu/V127/N21/jones.html |work=MIT Tech |date=April 27, 2007 |accessdate=2007-04-27}}</ref> and she had fabricated "a degree" from Albany Medical College "after she was hired."<ref name="Hoover"/> MIT administrators were alerted to the discrepancy on or around April 16, 2007. MIT has not released the name of the person or persons who alerted them about Jones's background.<ref name="TheTech"/> Jones issued a statement on the MIT web site, in which she admitted to wrongdoing: {{quote|I misrepresented my academic degrees when I first applied to MIT 28 years ago and did not have the courage to correct my resume when I applied for my current job or at any time since.<ref>[http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/2007/admissions-jones.html Statement of Marilee Jones], MIT website</ref>}}
A spokesperson from Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute reported on April 26, 2007, that Jones attended the institute as a "part-time, [[Matriculation#Special student|non-matriculating]] student" from September 1974 to June 1975 and did not receive a degree.<ref name="bloombergdegrees"> {{cite web | last = Sullivan | first = Brian K. | title = MIT Dean of Admissions Resigns, Citing False Resume (Update 5) | publisher = Bloomberg.com | date = 2007-04-26 | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=aaYOq9JkjWKk&refer=us | accessdate = 2007-04-26 }} </ref> Spokespeople from Union College and from Albany Medical College both reported that there are no records of Jones ever attending either institution.<ref name="bloombergdegrees"/> On May 2, 2007, it was reported that she had actually earned a bachelor's degree in biology from [[The College of Saint Rose]] in 1973, though she did not list that degree when applying for her first job at MIT or when being considered for subsequent promotions.<ref> {{cite web | last = Bombardieri | first = Marcella | title = Ex-MIT dean never cited actual degree | publisher = ''The Boston Globe'' | date = 2007-05-02 | url = http://www.boston.com/news/education/higher/articles/2007/05/02/ex_mit_dean_never_cited_actual_degree/ | accessdate = 2007-05-02 }} </ref>
When Jones was appointed to the position of Dean of Admissions in 1998, she was credited with having earned an "SB and an SM in biology from Rennselaer Polytechnic Institute" in an article published in ''[http://tech.mit.edu/V117/N65/djones.65n.html The Tech]''<ref>{{cite news | first=Susan | last=Buchman | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=New Director of Admissions Jones Appointed at Year End | date=1998-01-07 | publisher= ''The Tech'' | url =http://tech.mit.edu/V117/N65/djones.65n.html | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | language = }}</ref> as well as an article published by ''[http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/1997/jones-1217.html MIT Tech Talk]''.<ref>{{cite news | first=Sarah | last=Wright | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=Jones Is New Dean of Admissions | date=1997-12-17 | publisher= ''MIT News'' | url =http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/1997/jones-1217.html | work = | pages = | accessdate = 2009-12-11 | language = }}</ref> Neither article made any mention of the degree from Union College which she had placed on her resume in 1979 nor of a Ph.D. credited to her several times in 2007. Shortly before her resignation, she was referred to by the title "Dr. Marilee Jones" in a number of forums. A biography of her on the website for the 2007 September Conference of the [https://web.archive.org/web/20160121210648/http://www.nacacnet.org/Pages/default.aspx National Association of College Admission Counselors] referred to her as "Dr. Marilee Jones, Ph.D." and credited her with degrees from RPI and Albany Medical in biology and chemistry but offered no further details.<ref>{{cite web | last = Seward | first = Zachary | title = MIT Admissions Dean Resigns; Admits Misleading School on Credentials | publisher = ''The Harvard Crimson'' | date = 2007-04-26 | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2007/4/26/mit-admissions-dean-resigns-admits-misleading/ | accessdate = 2009-12-08 }}</ref> She was also referred to as "Dr. Marilee Jones" in the local Concord press in April 2007.<ref>{{cite web |last = Rifkin |first = Glenn |title = Battling stress before college |publisher = ''Wicked Local Concord'' |date = 2007-04-06 |url = http://www.wickedlocal.com/concord/news/lifestyle/columnists/x1640568211 |accessdate = 2009-12-08 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121108071207/http://www.wickedlocal.com/concord/news/lifestyle/columnists/x1640568211 |archivedate = 2012-11-08 |df = }}</ref> A February 2007 NPR transcript from ''All Things Considered'' referred to her as "Dr. Marilee Jones"<ref>{{cite web | last = | first = | title = Colleges Want to Cool Admissions Frenzy | publisher = NPR: ''All Things Considered'' | date = 2007-02-27 | url = https://www.npr.org/templates/transcript/transcript.php?storyId=7383744 | accessdate = 2009-12-08 }}</ref> (though the audio program itself did not address her as "Dr").<ref>{{cite web | last = Adler | first = Margot | title = Colleges Want to Cool Admissions Frenzy | publisher = NPR: ''All Things Considered'' | date = 2007-02-22 | url = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=7383744 | accessdate = 2009-12-08 }}</ref> And a brief bio of her for an April 17, 2007 speaking engagement at Kean University's Annual School Counselor Conference referred to her as "Dr. Marilee Jones."<ref>{{cite web| last =| first =| title =Annual School Counselor Conference| publisher =Kean University Office of Admissions| date =| url =http://www.kean.edu/forms/Admissions/Counselor%20Conference%20Booklet.pdf| accessdate =2009-12-08}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> When asked in a December 6, 2009 interview with the ''[http://chronicle.com Chronicle of Higher Education]'' about having added "a degree" from Albany Medical to her resume "after she was hired" by MIT, Jones did not dispute the fact. She could not, however, remember the details.<ref name="Hoover"/>
After her departure from MIT Jones created her own consulting firm which provides service for admissions both institutions and applicants.<ref>{{cite news | first=Tamar | last=Lewin | coauthors= |authorlink= | title=Former Dean Resurfaces, Leaving Scandal Behind | date=2009-12-07 | publisher= | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/08/education/08jones.html?_r=1&hpw | work =[[New York Times]] | pages = | accessdate = 2009-12-08 | language = }}</ref> She states she was also offered the position of Dean of Admissions at several undisclosed universities for which she declined.<ref>{{cite web | last = Lewin | first = Tamar | title = Dean Resurfaces, Leaving Scandal Behind | publisher = New York Times | date = 2009-12-07 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/08/education/08jones.html | accessdate = 2009-12-08 }}</ref>
In 2008, she hired Rose Marie Terenzio, a public relations consultant who was the former personal assistant of [[John F. Kennedy Jr]], to help her make a "reclamation," a "comeback."<ref name="Hoover"/>
==Awards== In 2001, Jones received MIT's Excellence Award for Leading Change, which recognized Jones's leadership as dean of admissions. An excerpt from the presentation reads: {{quote|Because of Marilee's leadership and passion, the message of: "science in the service of mankind," now resonates among generations of students. She helps students understand that they have a responsibility as members of society, to utilize their skills and talents to make a difference in the world. Marilee has also been visionary in her approach towards admissions strategies and processes, incorporating faculty and alumni perspectives, and the concerns and interests of prospective students and their parents.<ref name="mitawards">{{cite web |title=MIT Excellence Awards 2001 |publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] |year=2001 |url=http://web.mit.edu/hr/rewards/ex_past/2001_awards/LCscripts.html |accessdate=2007-04-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513233526/http://web.mit.edu/hr/rewards/ex_past/2001_awards/LCscripts.html |archivedate=2007-05-13 |deadurl=yes |df= }} </ref>}}
Jones also received MIT's Gordon Y. Billard Award "for special service of outstanding merit performed for the Institute"<ref name="mitbillard">{{cite web | title = Awards Convocation | publisher = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] | year = 2006 | url = http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/2006/awards-convo-0607.html | accessdate = 2007-04-30 }} </ref> in 2006.
==Personal== Jones is divorced from Steven R. Bussolari, an engineer at MIT's [[Lincoln Laboratory]]. They have one daughter.<ref name="Amazon" /> <ref name="NewDean"/><ref name="dwc"> {{cite web |title=Bussolari named to Daniel Webster College Board of Trustees |publisher=Daniel Webster College |year=2006 |url=http://www.dwc.edu/news/bussolari.shtml |accessdate=2007-04-26 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070112185004/http://www.dwc.edu/news/bussolari.shtml |archivedate=2007-01-12 |deadurl=yes |df= }} </ref><ref name="telegraph"> {{cite web | title = At MIT, a war on admission terror - Institute of over-achievers becomes Marilee Jones's launchpad for campaign to reduce student stress | publisher = ''[[The Telegraph (Kolkata)|The Telegraph]]'' | date = 2006-09-06 | url = http://www.telegraphindia.com/1060918/asp/atleisure/story_6760331.asp | accessdate = 2007-04-29 }} </ref> While still holding the position of dean of admissions at MIT, Jones delivered a speech at her daughter's 2006 commencement from [[Middlesex School]], advising the graduates to "create your own reality" and "give out what you want to get back". <ref name="norablast"> {{cite web |title=Middlesex School Graduation 2006 |publisher=Middlesex School |date=2006-06-02 |url=http://65.61.134.134/common/news_detail.asp?newsid=277116&L1=7&L2=1 |accessdate=2007-04-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927181847/http://65.61.134.134/common/news_detail.asp?newsid=277116&L1=7&L2=1 |archivedate=2007-09-27 |deadurl=yes |df= }} </ref>
