{{use dmy dates|date=June 2017}} {{Infobox School |name=Landesschule Pforta |image=Logo pforta.svg |imagesize=100px |caption=Logo of Pforta |streetaddress=Schulstr. 12 |postcode=06628 |city=Schulpforte |country=Germany |coordinates={{coord|51|08|33|N|11|45|08|E|type:edu|display=inline,title}} |rector=Thomas Schödel<ref>Landesschule Pforta: [http://www.landesschule-pforta.de/archiv/2012_13/allgemein.php "Inauguration des neuen Rektors"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731145433/http://www.landesschule-pforta.de/archiv/2012_13/allgemein.php |date=31 July 2013 }} from 31 October 2012</ref> |students=300 |classes=12 |avg_class_size=22 |type=[[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]] |language=German |yearbook=Keilzeit |colors=purple, white, black |staff=48 |opened=1543 |homepage=[http://www.landesschule-pforta.de/index.php?a=en http://www.landesschule-pforta.de] |}}
'''Pforta''', or '''Schulpforta''', is a school located in a former [[Cistercians|Cistercian]] [[monastery]], '''[[Pforta monastery]]''' (1137–1540), near [[Naumburg]] on the [[Saale River]] in the [[Germany|German]] state of [[Saxony-Anhalt]].
Since the 16th century the site has been a school. Notable past alumni include the philosopher [[Friedrich Nietzsche]] and the German chancellor [[Theobald von Bethmann-Hollweg]]. Today, it is a well-known [[public education|public]] [[boarding school]] for academically gifted children, called '''Landesschule Pforta'''. It is [[coeducation]]al and teaches around 300 [[high school]] students.
Pforta is proposed for inscription in the [[World Heritage Site|World Heritage List]] as one component of the German nomination [[Naumburg Cathedral and the High Medieval Cultural Landscape of the Rivers Saale and Unstrut]].
==History==
===Monastery=== [[File:Pforta Altes Schulhaus.jpg|thumb|left|Pforta, ''Altes Schulhaus'']] {{Main|Pforta monastery}}
The abbey was at first situated in [[Altenburger Land|Schmölln]] on the Sprotta, near [[Altenburg]]. In 1127, Count Bruno of Pleissengau founded a [[Order of St. Benedict|Benedictine]] monastery there and endowed it with 1,100 [[Hide (unit)|hides]] of land.{{sfn|Löffler|1911}} This foundation not being successful, on 23 April 1132, {{Interlanguage link multi|Udo I of Naumburg|de|3=Udo I. von Thüringen|lt=Bishop Udo I of Naumburg}}, a relative of Bruno's, replaced the Benedictines by Cistercian monks from [[Walkenried Abbey]]. The situation here proved undesirable, and in 1137 Udo transferred the monastery to Pforta, and conferred upon it fifty hides of arable land, an important tract of forest, and two farms belonging to the [[Diocese of Naumburg|diocese]].{{sfn|Löffler|1911}}
The [[Patron saint|patroness]] of the abbey was the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]]. The first abbot was Adalbert, from 1132 to 1152. Under the third abbot, Adetold, two daughter houses<!--?which--> were founded under Pforta's auspices, in the [[Marches|Mark]] of [[Meissen]] and in [[Silesia]], and in 1163, the monasteries of [[Altzella Abbey|Altzella]] and [[Leubus]] were also established in the latter province. At this period the monks numbered about eighty. In 1205, Pforta sent a colony of monks to [[Livonia]], founding there the monastery of [[Dünamünde]]. The abbey was distinguished for its excellent system of management, and after the first 140 years of its existence its possessions had increased tenfold.{{sfn|Löffler|1911}}
At the end of the 13th and the beginning of the 14th centuries, after a period of strife, the monastery flourished again. The last quarter of the 14th century witnessed, however, the gradual decline of its prosperity, and also the relaxation of monastic discipline. When Abbot Johannes IV was elected in 1515, there were forty-two monks and seven [[lay brother]]s who later revolted against the abbot; an inspection by [[George, Duke of Saxony|Duke George of Saxony]] reported that morality had ceased to exist in the monastery.{{sfn|Löffler|1911}}
The last abbot, Peter Schederich, was elected in 1533. When the [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]] Duke George was succeeded by his [[Protestantism|Protestant]] brother [[Henry IV, Duke of Saxony|Henry]], the monastery was suppressed on 9 November 1540, with the abbot, eleven monks, and four lay brothers being pensioned off.{{sfn|Löffler|1911}}
===Boarding school=== [[File:Schulpforte Fürstenhaus.jpg|thumb|right|''Fürstenhaus'']] In 1543, Henry's son [[Maurice, Elector of Saxony|Duke Moritz]] opened a national school in the abbey,<ref>[http://www.landesschule-pforta.de/index.php?a=en&z=intro Landesschule Pforta's English website]</ref> appropriating for its use the revenues of the suppressed monastery of [[Memleben Abbey]]. At first the number of scholars was 100; in 1563 fifty more could be accommodated. The first rector was [[Johann Gigas]], renowned as a lyric poet. Under [[Justinus Bertuch]] (1601–1626) the school attained the zenith of its prosperity. It suffered greatly during the [[Thirty Years' War]], in 1643, there being only eleven scholars.{{sfn|Löffler|1911}} After the [[Napoleonic Wars]] ended in 1815, Pforta belonged to [[Kingdom of Prussia|Prussia]], and then to [[Imperial Germany]].{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}
From 1935 until 1945 Schulpforta served as a ''Nationalpolitische Erziehungsanstalt'' (NPEA) or National Political Institution of Teaching. As an NPEA the institution was concerned with promoting National Socialist ([[Nazi]]) ideals and encouraging boys between the ages of 11 and 18 to pursue occupations (such as work within the [[Schutzstaffel]]/SS) which supported the National Socialist cause.<ref>http://helenroche.com/work/wanderer-kommst-du-nach-pforta</ref><ref>http://www.saale-unstrut-tourismus.de/en/pforta-abbey</ref>
In 1949, the institute became co-educational.{{sfn|''Landesschule Pforta''|2014}} Today the school is maintained by the German state of [[Saxony-Anhalt]], but still supported by its own Schulpforta Foundation.
==Architecture== The remains of the monastery include the 13th century [[Gothic architecture|gothic]] church;{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=340}} it is a cross-[[Vault (architecture)|vaulted]], [[colonnade]]d [[basilica]] with an extraordinarily long [[nave]], a peculiar western [[Facade|façade]], and a late [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] double-naved [[cloister]]. What remains of the original building (1137–40) is in the Romanesque style, while the restoration (1251–1268) belongs to the early Gothic.{{sfn|Löffler|1911}} Other buildings are now used as dormitories and lecture halls.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} There is also the ''Fürstenhaus'' ("prince's house"), built in 1573. Schulpforta was one of the three ''Fürstenschulen'' ("prince's schools") founded in 1543 by Maurice, Elector of Saxony (at that time Duke), the two others being at Grima and at Meissen.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911|p=340}}
== Notable pupils == Notable pupils include:{{citation needed|date=January 2017}} * [[Theobald von Bethmann-Hollweg]], German chancellor * [[August Buchner]] (1591–1661), influential Baroque poet * [[Johann Gottlieb Fichte]], philosopher * [[Friedrich Gottlieb Klopstock]], poet * [[Frederic Henry Hedge]], American Transcendentalist * [[Günther Lützow]], World War II fighter pilot * [[Johannes Mayer]], World War II officer * [[August Ferdinand Möbius]], mathematician * [[Ablai Kabash Maxatovich]], mathematician * [[Candice Pene Phit Inna Mouthe]], war captive (2nd reich)
* [[Friedrich Nietzsche]]<ref>Nietzsche attended Schulpforta from 1858 to 1864: [https://web.archive.org/web/20030114120835/http://www4.hmc.edu:8001/humanities/beckman/Nietzsche/biography.htm NIETZSCHE'S LIFE IN OUTLINE]</ref>, philosopher * [[Leopold von Ranke]], historian * [[Johann Christian Wernsdorf]], writer * [[Ulrich von Wilamowitz-Moellendorff]], classical philologist * [[Christian Gottfried Ehrenberg]], German naturalist
